
process: 
--> A process is a program in execution
--> it is simply a running instance of a program
--> A process is simply a program that is currently running


-types of processes:
1. foreground process:
--> A foreground process runs in the terminal and uses the terminal until it finishes.
--> you can not use the terminal for another command while it is running.
eg: gzip, find, mkdir

2. background process:
--> these processes runs in a background without blocking your terminal.
--> the terminal is free
--> you can continue typing other commands

3. daemon process:
--> A daemon process is a special background process that starts automatically
and keeps running to provide service.
eg: initd, sshd

-Runnning a proccess in background
--> use the & symbol to start a process in the background
eg:
command &
sleep 100&
sleep 60&

jobs: 
--> shows jobs started from the current terminal
--> used to manage background and stopped jobs
syntax: jobs

ps:
--> shows all running processes
--> used to check process details
--> shows system processes, deamon processes and user processes
syntax:
ps
ps -e: (e means every process)
ps -aux:
here
a = process of all users
u = user oriented format(shows user, cpu etc)
x = all processes

top: 
--> shows all system processes live (real time).
syntax: top

tree:
--> display files and directories in a tree like structure
syntax: tree

pstree:
-->process tree is a way to see which process started another process.
-->it is a hierarchical view of running process.
eg:
parent process
child process

parent process:
--> A process that stsrts or creates a new process is called the parent process.
eg:
--> the terminal starts the bash shell.

child process:
--> Achild process is the process that is created by the parent process.
--> when you type ls command. bash creates a new process to run the ls command.
so here
bash is parent process
ls is child process

**Main Process states**
1. R = running
2. S = sleeping
-->process is waiting for something.(keyboard input, file, network) 
3. T = stopped
4. Z = Zombie
-->process has finished execution, but its parent has not yet collected its exit status
-->A child process has ended but the parent has not acknowledged it yet.

**process Priority**
--> nice and renice value/commands are used to manage process priorities.
-20 = highest Priority
20 = lowest priority 

-20 --> very high priority (gets CPU sooner)
19 --> low priority (waits longer)

sleep 60 --> -15
sleep 100 --> 2

ps -l pid
--> used to check process nice value

renice -n <nice_value> <pid>
--> to change process priority
here,
-n : specifies the nice value
<nice value> : the priority adjusment (from -20 to 20)
<pid> : running process id

nice -n <nice_value> <command>
--> to set process priority

kill:
--> used to terminate a process manually
syntax:
kill -9 <pid>
here,
-9 = forecfully terminate process
eg:
kill -9 2600


